  "text": "We also identify two cases of social welfare functions over strict incomplete orders where it is possible to satisfy at the same time independence to irrelevant alternatives, unanimity and non-dictatorship. One of such cases corresponds to the generalization of Sen's theorem for majority voting over strict complete orders [CITATION_1] . The second case concerns profiles with no chain of ordered pairs. We then consider the notion of strategy-proofness, which denotes the non-manipulability of a social choice function. The Gibbard-Satterthwaite result [CITATION_2] tells us that it is not possible for a social choice function defined over strict complete orders to be at same time non-manipulable and have no dictators. We prove that this result holds also when the social choice function is defined over strict incomplete orders. To do this, we first generalize the notion of strategy-proofness to partially ordered preferences.",
